TL;DR: visual markers are used in drug development to understand where the drug goes in the body (in animal models) and then removed entirely for human use
Humans do not have bioluminescent proteins and therefore our bodies would view them as foreign and mount an immune response. Which defeats the purpose of a therapeutic.

Where does this connect to humans? For some therapeutics, markers are used to find out where the treatment goes in animal models, and THAT IS ALL. By the time the therapeutic makes it to humans, precautions are taken to ensure that none of these markers are expressed.
Sometimes this is actually purely visual, sometimes it’s detectable only by instruments (fluorescence/radiation). But this is all done to understand where in the body molecules are traveling.

Other times we use visual markers to track where shit is going. Some therapeutics need to travel to a certain part of the body to be effective. When developing a drug, research uses visual markers to track where the drug molecules are going.

Someone is sharing this internal BioNTech report about luciferase (an enzyme responsible for bioluminescence, where animals make their own light) and all you need to know is that FREQUENTLY in biotech we use fluorescence or other markers to track success
